The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, August 11, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, Aug. 10: British Airways is raising its ticket prices from tomorrow on all long-haul flights, including those from India, because of the rise in fuel costs. The ticket prices will go up because of the increase in fuel surcharge on long-haul flights from 2.50 per sector to 4.3 per sector ($8 per sector) on all new bookings made in India as a result of the continuing increase in the price of oil, a spokesperson said. 																								 Chennai, Aug. 10: The Centre had permitted Fiat India to write off the accumulated loss of Rs 1,300 crore incurred by predecessor Premier Automobiles. Although the Centres clearance was obtained last year, the loss was written off only during the current fiscal (January-December) of the company,  said director Ravi Bhardwaj.																								 Calcutta, Aug. 10: Tata Steel today signed the annual bonus agreement with Tata Workers Union. The pact is linked to production and profitability for 2003-04. Under it, the workers would be paid 20 per cent of annual salary or wage each, the minimum of which will be Rs 13,687 and the maximum Rs 55,768.																								 Mumbai, Aug. 10: BPO major Tricom India has acquired Tricom document management Inc of the US for $20,000.
